edictus, your fairly wrong about a good part of your argument.<br>
<br>
1. LotR has almost -nothing- to do with the american movie industry (Hollywood) with the exception of it being a i.) New Line Movie and ii.) NL's marketing strategy. The entire movie was filmed in New Zealand, by a NZ director, using an unknown NZ sfx company. If the movie were to be "americanized" the entire thing could have easily been shot in a soundstage in downtown cali anytime.<br>
<br>
2. Peter Jackson (the director) is a self admitted tolkien fiend. There's a quote somewhere from a "Studio Boss" which reads something like, "Once we realzied [Peter Jackson's] utter devotiona nd love for turning these books into a movie, we just sat back and let him create his vision". Or something along those lines. The only major "$$" pushes New Line did were the marketing strategies. But then again, if -you- were the head of a failing movie company, wouldnt you?? LotR had to do this a lot, seeing as how they were primarily up against an almost purely  capatalistic venture (the Harry Potter movie).<br>
<br>
3. Fantasy does -not- make good money in the theater. Harry Potter is the -only- recent movie to, and thats because it was designed to be a BIG box office bang, and then drop off. Need I remind you of "The Mummy Returns" or the D&D movie?<br>
<br>
4. The famous Arwen debate... wouldnt it be pretty strange for the audience if all of a sudden at the end of Return of the King, this -never before mentioned- character comes in and is all of a sudden becomes a major player? I think if I had never read the book I'd be confused. So he replaces Glorfindel at the ford with her... a total of >10 min screen time. <br>
<br>
5. Almost every review I've read so far has praised this movie as being one of the best movies in the past year or even decade. Not to sound too much like a fanboy, but that's hopeful for the entire genre. Read them for yourself: <a href="http://http://imladris.net/?getnews=1142">HERE</a>. Do I expect TTT and RotK to be more marketed? Yes I do. <br>
<br>
Now, do -I- think LotR will be a good movie? YES.<br>
Do I think that LotR will be the LotR I've read? NO.<br>
<br>
For all you "purists" out there you gotta realize that no book adaptation is going to be 100% true to the book... remember... its an ADAPTATION. Chill out, and stop taking Tolkien's book as the word of god.<br>
<br>
/rant off.<br>
